 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;a. &quot;">
      Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> satisfy one of the equivalent conditions of <fr:ref
addr="sga1-i.3.1"
href="sga1-i.3.1.xml"
taxon="Proposition"
number="I.3.1" />.
      Then we say that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>unramified</fr:em> at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>, or that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is unramified at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>

    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;b. &quot;">
      Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\to  B]]></fr:tex> be a local homomorphism.
      We say that it is <fr:em>unramified</fr:em>, or that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is a local <fr:em>unramified</fr:em> algebra on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B/\mathfrak {r}(A)B]]></fr:tex> is a finite separable extension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A/\mathfrak {r}(A)]]></fr:tex>, i.e. if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {r}(A)B=\mathfrak {r}(B)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k(B)]]></fr:tex> is a separable extension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k(A)]]></fr:tex>.
      (cf. regrets in [III 1.2])
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
