type="machine">#273</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-273.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Remarks</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>sga1-i.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:ul><fr:li>In the case where we don't suppose that the residue extension is trivial, we can reduce to the case where it is by taking a suitable finite flat extension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> which destroys the aforementioned extension.</fr:li>
    <fr:li>Consider the example where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is the local ring of an ordinary double point of a curve, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> a point of its normalisation:
      then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subset  B]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is unramified over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> with trivial residue extension, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\widehat {A}\to \widehat {B}]]></fr:tex> is surjective but <fr:em>not injective</fr:em>.
      We are thus going to strengthen the notion of unramified-ness.</fr:li></fr:ul></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
